Executive Summary
The company’s supply chain performance in Q1 2026 shows critical issues with premium skincare replenishment in high-demand North and East regions, inconsistent supplier service in low-sales regions, and misaligned inventory policies across categories. Premium skincare, the highest-margin segment, faces stockouts and delays that hurt availability and sales growth, particularly in the North and East. Budget skincare suffers from falling demand and poor availability in low-sales regions, risking market presence. Additionally, siloed data management between sales and inventory teams is slowing decision-making. To improve service levels, reduce stockouts, and optimize inventory, differentiated replenishment strategies and supplier management actions are urgently needed.

Priority Issues

Premium Skincare Stockouts & Delays:

North region has only 5 days cover with no incoming stock confirmed; East region’s 4 days cover is compounded by a 7-day delay of 300 units from Supplier A, resulting in a low fill rate (84%).
Rising demand trends in North and East heighten the risk of lost sales and margin erosion.
Supplier Performance & Escalation:

Supplier A’s delayed deliveries and unconfirmed orders in key regions signal procurement inefficiencies.
Supplier B shows inconsistent service in low-sales regions, impacting budget skincare availability (68% fill rate).
Absence of formal escalation limits leverage to improve supplier responsiveness.
Inventory Imbalance & Demand Mismatch:

Budget makeup demand is falling in multiple regions yet inventory levels remain high, leading to excess stock and tied-up capital.
Budget skincare faces declining demand and frequent stockouts in low-sales regions, risking loss of presence.
Data & Stock Policy Silos:

Separate spreadsheets for sales and inventory delays stock decisions and impedes agile response to changing demand.
Uniform stock rules across all products fail to reflect differing demand volatility and margin priorities.
90-Day Action Plan

Resolve Premium Skincare Replenishment Issues:

Immediately confirm and expedite pending North region replenishment orders with Supplier A.
Collaborate with Supplier A to clear East region delays; consider alternative logistics or expedited shipping.
Increase safety stock levels and reorder frequency for premium skincare in North and East to buffer against volatility.
Strengthen Supplier Management:

Issue formal escalation notes to Supplier A and Supplier B focused on delivery reliability and service consistency.
Initiate monthly supplier performance reviews aligned with KPIs (OTIF, fill rate).
Explore secondary suppliers or contingency sourcing for critical SKUs in premium skincare and budget skincare categories.
Align Inventory with Demand & Profitability:

Reduce budget makeup replenishment in regions with declining demand to cut excess inventory and free cash.
Implement targeted stock replenishment in low-sales regions for budget skincare to improve availability and prevent stockouts.
Differentiate stock rules by product tier: higher service levels and buffer stocks for premium skincare; leaner stocks for budget makeup.
Integrate Data and Improve Decision-Making:

Deploy a shared dashboard or centralized system for sales and inventory teams to enable real-time stock visibility and demand insights.
Train teams on coordinated demand planning and dynamic replenishment adjustments based on real-time data.
Expected Business Impact

Improved Service Levels: Ensuring timely premium skincare availability in North and East will increase fill rates above 90%, supporting margin growth and customer satisfaction.
Reduced Stockouts and Lost Sales: Targeted replenishment in low-sales regions will stabilize budget skincare presence and reduce stockout rates below 5%.
Lower Inventory Carrying Costs: Aligning inventory with falling demand in budget makeup will reduce excess inventory by at least 20%, freeing capital for growth areas.
Enhanced Supplier Performance: Formal escalation and review processes will improve OTIF beyond 95%, reducing delays and disruptions.
Faster, Data-Driven Decisions: Integrated data platforms will accelerate replenishment responsiveness, enabling proactive adjustments to demand shifts and reducing forecast errors.
By focusing on these prioritized actions, the company will strengthen its supply chain agility, optimize inventory investments, and better serve evolving regional demand profiles, securing competitive advantage in a dynamic market.
